Step 1: Identify the components to be used in the ratio calculation.
• Cash includes "Cash on Hand" and "Bank Deposits."
• Current Debt (or Current Liabilities) includes items such as "Accounts Payable" and "Taxes Payable."

Step 2: Extract the data from the balance sheet.
• Cash on Hand (end amount): 4,058,544.03
• Bank Deposits (end amount): 3,079,000.00
• Total Cash = 4,058,544.03 + 3,079,000.00 = 7,137,544.03

• Accounts Payable (end amount): 381,000.00
• Taxes Payable (end amount): 243,988.48
• Total Current Liabilities = 381,000.00 + 243,988.48 = 624,988.48

Step 3: Calculate the Cash to Current Debt Ratio.
Ratio = Total Cash / Total Current Liabilities = 7,137,544.03 / 624,988.48 ≈ 11.42
